# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: double-entry-accounting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Accounting software is typically composed of various modules, with different sections dealing with particular areas of accounting.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Note that vendors may use differing names for these modules.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] In many cases, implementation (i.e. the installation and configuration of the system at the client) can be a bigger consideration than the actual software chosen when it comes down to the total cost of ownership for the business.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Most mid-market and larger applications are sold exclusively through resellers, developers, and consultants.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Those organizations generally pass on a license fee to the software vendor and then charge the client for installation, customization, and support services.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Clients can normally count on paying roughly 50-200% of the price of the software in implementation and consulting fees.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Personal accounting software is simple in design and is used mostly for individuals.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Some activities that it supports are accounts payable-type accounting transactions, managing budgets, and simple account reconciliation.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] It is relatively inexpensive compared to the other accounting options.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] One of the more common uses of personal accounting software is for tax preparation.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] This software is used to file tax returns in a format suitable with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] An example of such software would be TurboTax.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] At the low-end of the business markets, inexpensive applications software allows most general business accounting functions to be performed.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Suppliers frequently serve a single national market, while larger suppliers offer separate solutions in each national market.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Many of the low end products are characterized by being "single-entry" products, as opposed to double-entry systems seen in many businesses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Some products have considerable functionality but are not considered GAAP or IFRS/FASB compliant.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Some low-end systems do not have adequate security nor audit trails.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] The mid-market covers a wide range of business software that may be capable of serving the needs of multiple national accountancy standards and allow accounting in multiple currencies.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] In addition to general accounting functions, the software may include integrated or add-on management information systems, and may be oriented towards one or more markets, for example with integrated or add-on project accounting modules.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Accounting software for large organizations was typically the province of mainframe computers.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Organizations could either develop their own software, to model their internal financial processes, or buy a commercial package and tailor it to their needs.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] By the 1970s and 1980s, some of the software companies making accounting packages for the IBM mainframe market were Management Science America, McCormack & Dodge, Walker Interactive Products, Informatics General, and Cullinet Software.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Over time, the most complex and expensive business accounting software became frequently part of an extensive suite of software often known as enterprise resource planning (ERP) software.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] These applications typically have a very long implementation period, often greater than six months.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] In many cases, these applications are simply a set of functions which require significant integration, configuration and customization to even begin to resemble an accounting system.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Many freeware high-end open-source accounting software are available online these days which aim to change the market dynamics.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Most of these software solutions are web-based.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] The advantage of a high-end solution is that these systems are designed to support individual company specific processes, as they are highly customizable and can be tailored to exact business requirements.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] This usually comes at a significant cost in terms of money and implementation time.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] As technology improves, software vendors have been able to offer increasingly advanced software at lower prices.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] This software is suitable for companies at multiple stages of growth.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Many of the features of mid-market and high-end software (including advanced customization and extremely scalable databases) are required even by small businesses as they open multiple locations or grow in size.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Additionally, with more and more companies expanding overseas or allowing workers to home office, many smaller clients have a need to connect multiple locations.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Their options are to employ software-as-a-service or another application that offers them similar accessibility from multiple locations over the internet.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] With the advent of faster computers and internet connections, accounting software companies have been able to create accounting software which is paid for on a monthly recurring charge instead of a larger upfront license fee (software as a service - SaaS).
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] The rate of adoption of this new business model has increased steadily to the point where legacy players have been forced to come out with their own online versions.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Cloud accounting software is where financial information can be accessed from any device connected to the Internet at any time even though the financial data itself is located at a centralized computer.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] This differs from more traditional accounting software as it is restricted to a certain computer or system of computers and that accounting information can not be easily accessed from other devices.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Some reasons cloud accounting software is preferred by users is there is no need to worry about maintenance or hardware system upgrades, it can reduce overall costs, and that a user can gain access from multiple locations.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] One of the primary reasons cloud accounting software is not being used is the threat of the security of the data.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Privacy in cloud computing is in constant risk of disclosure when in possession of a third party.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Factors resulting in distrust of privacy include unauthorization, unpredictability, and nonconformity.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Security threats vary from different cloud environments and interactions and can cause significant risks that must be considered specific to that origin.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Unauthorization is a threat stemming from allowing third party organizations to handle an individual's data and the user not having full control.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Lack of user control is the effect of keeping data in the cloud, as opposed to one's own local host, and increases user's level of unpredictability.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] Legislative complexity impacts cloud computing in where the data is being stored and the laws that data in that location, or locations, must follow.
[src:double-entry-accounting/accounting-software] While cloud computing and traditional IT environments may pose differing privacy issues, the security controls are generally similar.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] A **chart of accounts** (**COA**) is a list of financial accounts and reference numbers, grouped into categories, such as assets, liabilities, equity, revenue and expenses, and used for recording transactions in the organization's general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Accounts may be associated with an identifier (account number) and a caption or header and are coded by account type.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] In computerized accounting systems with computable quantity accounting, the accounts can have a quantity measure definition.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Account numbers may consist of numerical, alphabetic, or alpha-numeric characters, although in many computerized environments, like the SIE format, only numerical identifiers are allowed.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The structure and headings of accounts should assist in consistent posting of transactions.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Each nominal ledger account is unique, which allows its ledger to be located.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The accounts are typically arranged in the order of the customary appearance of accounts in the financial statements: balance sheet accounts followed by profit and loss accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The charts of accounts can be picked from a standard chart of accounts, like the BAS in Sweden.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] In some countries, charts of accounts are defined by the accountant from a standard general layouts or as regulated by law.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] However, in most countries it is entirely up to each accountant to design the chart of accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] A chart of accounts is usually created for an organization by an accountant and available for use by the bookkeeper.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Each account in the chart of accounts is typically assigned a name.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Accounts may also be assigned a unique account number by which the account can be identified.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Account numbers may be structured to suit the needs of an organization, such as digit/s representing a division of the company, a department, the type of account, etc.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The first digit might, for example, signify the type of account (asset, liability, etc.).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] In accounting software, using the account number may be a more rapid way to post to an account, and allows accounts to be presented in numeric order rather than alphabetic order.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] However, a balanced trial balance does not guarantee that there are no errors in the individual ledger entries.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Accounts may be added to the chart of accounts as needed; they would not generally be removed, especially if any transaction had been posted to the account or if there is a non-zero balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] While some countries define standard national charts of accounts (for example France and Germany) others such as the United States and United Kingdom do not.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] In the European Union, most countries codify a national GAAP (consistent with the EU accounting directives) and also require IFRS (as outlined by the IAS regulation) for public companies.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The former often define a chart of accounts while the latter does not.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] However, since national GAAPs often serve as the basis for determining income tax, and since income tax law is reserved for the member states, no single uniform EU chart of accounts exists.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Liability accounts** are used to recognize liabilities.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] A liability is a present obligation of an entity to transfer an economic benefit (CF E37).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Common examples of liability accounts include accounts payable, deferred revenue, bank loans, bonds payable and lease obligations.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Equity accounts** are used to recognize ownership equity.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The terms equity [for profit enterprise] or net assets [not-for-profit enterprise] represent the residual interest in the assets of an entity that remains after deducting its liabilities (CF E61).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Equity accounts include common stock, paid-in capital, and retained earnings.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Equity accounts can vary depending where an entity is domiciled as some jurisdictions require entities to keep various sub-classifications of equity in separate accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Revenue accounts** are used to recognize revenue.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Revenues are inflows or other enhancements of assets of an entity or settlements of its liabilities (or a combination of both) from delivering or producing goods, rendering services, or carrying out other activities (CF E80).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Expense accounts** are used to recognize expenses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Expenses are outflows or other using up of assets of an entity or incurrences of its liabilities (or a combination of both) from delivering or producing goods, rendering services, or carrying out other activities (CF E81).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Gain accounts** are used to recognize gains.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Gains are increases in equity (net assets) from transactions and other events and circumstances affecting an entity except those that result from revenues or investments by owners (CF E82).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] In practice, changes in the market value of assets (positive) or liabilities (negative) are recognized as gains while, for example, interest, dividends, rent or royalties received are recognized as other revenue.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Loss accounts** are used to recognize losses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Losses are decreases in equity (net assets) from transactions and other events and circumstances affecting an entity except those that result from expenses or distributions to owners (CF E83).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] In practice, changes in the market value of assets (negative) or liabilities (positive) are recognized as losses while, for example, interest or charitable contributions are recognized as other expenses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Income** is the term generally used when referring to revenue and gains together.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] A separate term for the aggregation of expenses and losses does not exist.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] **Contra-accounts** are accounts with negative balances that offset other balance sheet accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Examples are accumulated depreciation (offset against fixed assets), and the allowance for bad debts (offset against accounts receivable).
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Deferred interest is also offset against receivables rather than being classified as a liability.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] Contra accounts are also often referred to as adjustments or adjusting accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] A chart of accounts compatible with IFRS and US GAAP includes balance sheet (assets, liabilities and equity) and the profit and loss (revenue, expenses, gains and losses) classifications.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] If used by a consolidated or combined entity, it also includes separate classifications for intercompany transactions and balances.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The French generally accepted accounting principles chart of accounts layout is used in France, Belgium, Spain and many francophone countries.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The use of the French GAAP chart of accounts layout (but not the detailed accounts) is stated in French law.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] In France, liabilities and equity are seen as negative assets and not account types in themselves, just balance accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The Spanish generally accepted accounting principles chart of accounts layout is used in Spain.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] It is very similar to the French layout.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The complete Swedish BAS standard chart of about 1250 accounts is also available in English and German texts in a printed publication from the non-profit branch BAS organisation.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The BAS chart use is not legally required in Sweden.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] However, it is politically anchored and so well developed that it is commonly used.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] The BAS chart is not an SIS national standard because SIS is organised on pay documentation and nobody in the computer world are paying for standard documents.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] SIS Swedish Standards Institute is the Swedish domestic member of ISO.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] This is not a government procurement problem due to the fact all significant governmental authorities are significant members/part owners of BAS.
[src:double-entry-accounting/chart-of-accounts] An almost identical chart of accounts is used in Norway.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Debits increase the value of assets and expense accounts and reduce the value of liabilities, equity, and revenue accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Conversely, credits increase the value of liability, equity, and revenue accounts and reduce the value of asset and expense accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Debits and credits are traditionally distinguished by writing the transfer amounts in separate columns of an account book.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This practice simplified the manual calculation of net balances before the introduction of computers; each column was added separately, and then the smaller total was subtracted from the larger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Alternatively, debits and credits can be listed in one column, indicating debits with the suffix "Dr" or writing them plain, and indicating credits with the suffix "Cr" or a minus sign.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Debits and credits do not, however, correspond in a fixed way to positive and negative numbers.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Instead the correspondence depends on the normal balance convention of the particular account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The modern double entry system was likely a direct precursor of the first European adaptation many centuries later.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The first known use of the terms "debit" and "credit" occurred in the Venetian Luca Pacioli's 1494 work, *Summa de Arithmetica, Geometria, Proportioni et Proportionalita* (*A Summary of Arithmetic, Geometry, Proportions and Proportionality*).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Pacioli devoted one section of his book to documenting and describing the double-entry bookkeeping system in use during the Renaissance by Venetian merchants, traders and bankers.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This system is still the fundamental system in use by modern bookkeepers.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] It is sometimes said that, in its original Latin, Pacioli's *Summa* used the Latin words *debere* (to owe) and *credere* (to entrust) to describe the two sides of a closed accounting transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Assets were owed to the owner and the owners' equity was entrusted to the company.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] At the time negative numbers were not in use.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] When his work was translated, the Latin words *debere* and *credere* became the English *debit* and *credit*.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Under this theory, the abbreviations Dr (for debit) and Cr (for credit) derive directly from the original Latin.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] However, Sherman casts doubt on this idea because Pacioli uses *Per* (Italian for "by") for the debtor and *A* (Italian for "to") for the creditor in the Journal entries.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The words actually used by Pacioli for the left and right sides of the Ledger are "in dare" and "in havere" (*give* and *receive*).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] To determine whether to debit or credit a specific account, we use either the modern *accounting equation* approach (based on five accounting rules), or the *classical approach* (based on three 'golden rules').
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Whether a *debit* increases or decreases an account's net balance depends on what kind of account it is.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The basic principle is that the account receiving benefit is debited, while the account giving benefit is credited.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For instance, an increase in an *asset* account is a debit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] An increase in a *liability* or an *equity* account is a credit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Debits and credits occur simultaneously in every financial transaction in double-entry bookkeeping.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In the accounting equation, **Assets = Liabilities + Equity**, so, if an asset account increases (a debit (left)), then either another asset account must decrease (a credit (right)), or a liability or equity account must increase (a credit (right)).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In the extended equation, revenues increase equity, while expenses, costs, and dividends decrease equity, so their difference is the impact on the equation.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For example, if a company provides a service to a customer who does not pay immediately, the company records an increase in assets, Accounts Receivable with a debit entry, and an increase in Revenue, with a credit entry.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] When the company receives the cash from the customer, two accounts again change on the company side, the cash account is debited (increased) and the Accounts Receivable account is now decreased (credited).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] When the cash is deposited to the bank account, two things also change from the bank's perspective: the bank records an increase in its cash account (debit) and records an increase in its liability to the customer by recording a credit in the customer's account (which is not cash).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Note that, technically, the deposit is not a decrease in the cash (asset) of the company and should not be recorded as such.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] It is just a transfer to a proper bank account of record in the company's books, not affecting the ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] To make it clearer, the bank views the transaction from a different perspective but follows the same rules: the bank's vault cash (asset) increases, which is a debit; the increase in the customer's account balance (liability from the bank's perspective) is a credit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A customer's periodic bank statement generally shows transactions from the bank's perspective, with cash deposits characterized as credits (liabilities) and withdrawals as debits (reductions in liabilities) in depositor's accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In the company's books the exact opposite entries should be recorded to account for the same cash.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This concept is important since this is why so many people misunderstand what debit/credit really means.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] When setting up the accounting for a new business, a number of accounts are established to record all business transactions that are expected to occur.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Typical accounts that relate to almost every business are: Cash, Accounts Receivable, Inventory, Accounts Payable and Retained Earnings.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Each account can be broken down further, to provide additional detail as necessary.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For example: Accounts Receivable can be broken down to show each customer that owes the company money.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In simplistic terms, if Bob, Dave, and Roger owe the company money, the Accounts Receivable account will contain a separate account for Bob, and Dave and Roger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] All 3 of these accounts would be added together and shown as a single number (i.e. total 'Accounts Receivable' – balance owed) on the balance sheet.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] All accounts for a company are grouped together and summarized on the balance sheet in 3 sections which are: Assets, Liabilities and Equity.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] All accounts must first be classified as one of the five types of accounts (accounting elements) (asset, liability, equity, income and expense).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] To determine how to classify an account into one of the five elements, the definitions of the five account types must be fully understood.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The definition of an asset according to IFRS is as follows, "An asset is a resource controlled by the entity as a result of past events from which future economic benefits are expected to flow to the entity".
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In simplistic terms, this means that Assets are accounts viewed as having a future value to the company (i.e. cash, accounts receivable, equipment, computers).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Liabilities, conversely, would include items that are obligations of the company (i.e. loans, accounts payable, mortgages, debts).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The Equity section of the balance sheet typically shows the value of any outstanding shares that have been issued by the company as well as its earnings.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] All Income and expense accounts are summarized in the Equity Section in one line on the balance sheet called Retained Earnings.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This account, in general, reflects the cumulative profit (retained earnings) or loss (retained deficit) of the company.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The Profit and Loss Statement is an expansion of the Retained Earnings Account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] It breaks-out all the Income and expense accounts that were summarized in Retained Earnings.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The Profit and Loss report is important in that it shows the detail of sales, cost of sales, expenses and ultimately the profit of the company.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Most companies rely heavily on the profit and loss report and review it regularly to enable strategic decision making.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The words **debit** and **credit** can sometimes be confusing because they depend on the point of view from which a transaction is observed.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In accounting terms, assets are recorded on the left side (debit) of asset accounts, because they are typically shown on the left side of the accounting equation (*A=L+SE*).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Likewise, an increase in liabilities and shareholder's equity are recorded on the right side (credit) of those accounts, thus they also maintain the balance of the accounting equation.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In other words, if "assets are increased with left side entries, the accounting equation is balanced only if increases in liabilities and shareholder’s equity are recorded on the opposite or right side.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Conversely, decreases in assets are recorded on the right side of asset accounts, and decreases in liabilities and equities are recorded on the left side".
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Similar is the case with revenues and expenses, what increases shareholder's equity is recorded as credit because they are in the right side of equation and vice versa.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Typically, when reviewing the financial statements of a business, Assets are Debits and Liabilities and Equity are Credits.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For example, when two companies transact with one another say Company A buys something from Company B then Company A will record a decrease in cash (a Credit), and Company B will record an increase in cash (a Debit).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The same transaction is recorded from two different perspectives.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This use of the terms can be counter-intuitive to people unfamiliar with bookkeeping concepts, who may always think of a credit as an increase and a debit as a decrease.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This is because most people typically only see their personal bank accounts and billing statements (e.g., from a utility).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A depositor's bank account is actually a Liability to the bank, because the bank legally owes the money to the depositor.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Thus, when the customer makes a deposit, the bank credits the account (increases the bank's liability).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] At the same time, the bank adds the money to its own cash holdings account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Since this account is an Asset, the increase is a debit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] But the customer typically does not see this side of the transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] On the other hand, when a utility customer pays a bill or the utility corrects an overcharge, the customer's account is credited.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This is because the customer's account is one of the utility's accounts receivable, which are Assets to the utility because they represent money the utility can expect to receive from the customer in the future.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Credits actually decrease Assets (the utility is now owed less money).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] If the credit is due to a bill payment, then the utility will add the money to its own cash account, which is a debit because the account is another Asset.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Again, the customer views the credit as an increase in the customer's own money and does not see the other side of the transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Debit cards and credit cards are creative terms used by the banking industry to market and identify each card.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] From the cardholder's point of view, a credit card account normally contains a credit balance, a debit card account normally contains a debit balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A debit card is used to make a purchase with one's own money.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A credit card is used to make a purchase by borrowing money.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] From the bank's point of view, when a debit card is used to pay a merchant, the payment causes a decrease in the amount of money the bank *owes to* the cardholder.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] From the bank's point of view, your debit card account is the bank's liability.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A decrease to the bank's liability account is a debit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] From the bank's point of view, when a credit card is used to pay a merchant, the payment causes an increase in the amount of money the bank *is owed by* the cardholder.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] From the bank's point of view, your credit card account is the bank's asset.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] An increase to the bank's asset account is a debit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Hence, using a debit card *or* credit card causes a debit to the cardholder's account in either situation when viewed from the bank's perspective.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] General ledger is the term for the comprehensive collection of T-accounts (it is so called because there was a pre-printed vertical line in the middle of each ledger page and a horizontal line at the top of each ledger page, like a large letter T).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Before the advent of computerized accounting, manual accounting procedure used a ledger book for each T-account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The collection of all these books was called the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The *chart of accounts* is the table of contents of the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Totaling of all debits and credits in the general ledger at the end of a financial period is known as *trial balance*.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] "Daybooks" or journals are used to list every single transaction that took place during the day, and the list is totaled at the end of the day.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] These daybooks are not part of the double-entry bookkeeping system.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The information recorded in these daybooks is then transferred to the general ledgers, where it is said to be *posted*.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Modern computer software allows for the instant update of each ledger account; for example, when recording a cash receipt in a cash receipts journal a debit is posted to a cash ledger account with a corresponding credit to the ledger account from which the cash was received.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Not every single transaction needs to be entered into a T-account; usually only the sum (the batch total) for the day of each book transaction is entered in the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] There are five fundamental elements within accounting.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] These elements are as follows: Assets, Liabilities, Equity (or Capital), Income (or Revenue) and Expenses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The five accounting elements are all affected in either a positive or negative way.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A credit transaction does not always dictate a positive value or increase in a transaction and similarly, a debit does not always indicate a negative value or decrease in a transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] An asset account is often referred to as a "debit account" due to the account's standard *increasing* attribute on the debit side.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The "X" in the debit column denotes the increasing effect of a transaction on the asset *account balance* (total debits less total credits), because a debit to an asset account is an increase.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The asset account above has been *added to* by a debit value X, i.e. the balance has increased by £X or $X.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Likewise, in the liability account below, the X in the credit column denotes the increasing effect on the liability account balance (total credits less total debits), because a credit to a liability account is an increase.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Personal accounts are liabilities and owners' equity and represent people and entities that have invested in the business.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Nominal accounts are revenue, expenses, gains, and losses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Accountants close out accounts at the end of each accounting period.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] This method is known as the traditional approach.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Each transaction that takes place within the business will consist of at least one debit to a specific account and at least one credit to another specific account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A debit to one account can be balanced by more than one credit to other accounts, and vice versa.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For all transactions, the total debits must be equal to the total credits and therefore *balance*.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The equation thus becomes A – L – E = 0 (zero).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] When the total debits equals the total credits for each account, then the equation balances.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In this form, increases to the amount of accounts on the left-hand side of the equation are recorded as debits, and decreases as credits.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Conversely for accounts on the right-hand side, increases to the amount of accounts are recorded as credits to the account, and decreases as debits.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] where the relationship of the Income and Expenses accounts to Equity and profit is a bit clearer.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Here Revenue and Expenses are regarded as temporary or nominal accounts which pertain only to the current accounting period whereas Asset, Liability, and Equity accounts are permanent or real accounts pertaining to the lifetime of the business.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The temporary accounts are closed to the Equity account at the end of the accounting period to record profit/loss for the period.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Both sides of these equations must be equal (balance).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Each transaction is recorded in a ledger or "T" account, e.g. a ledger account named "Bank" that can be changed with either a debit or credit transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Accounts are created/opened when the need arises for whatever purpose or situation the entity may have.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For example, if your business is an airline company they will have to purchase airplanes, therefore even if an account is not listed below, a bookkeeper or accountant can create an account for a specific item, such as an asset account for airplanes.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] In order to understand how to classify an account into one of the five elements, a good understanding of the *definitions* of these accounts is required.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Asset accounts are economic resources which benefit the business/entity and will continue to do so.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] They are Cash, bank, accounts receivable, inventory, land, buildings/plant, machinery, furniture, equipment, supplies, vehicles, trademarks and patents, goodwill, prepaid expenses, prepaid insurance, debtors (people who owe us money, due within one year), VAT input etc.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Liability accounts record debts or future obligations a business or entity owes to others.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] When one institution borrows from another for a period of time, the ledger of the borrowing institution categorises the argument under liability accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Equity accounts record the claims of the owners of the business/entity to the assets of that business/entity.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Capital, retained earnings, drawings, common stock, accumulated funds, etc.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Income accounts record all increases in Equity other than that contributed by the owner/s of the business/entity.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Services rendered, sales, interest income, membership fees, rent income, interest from investment, recurring receivables, donation etc.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Expense accounts record all decreases in the owners' equity which occur from using the assets or increasing liabilities in delivering goods or services to a customer – the costs of doing business.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Telephone, water, electricity, repairs, salaries, wages, depreciation, amortization, bad debts, stationery, entertainment, honorarium, rent, fuel, utility, interest etc.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Quick Services business purchases a computer for £500, on credit, from ABC Computers.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Quick Services has acquired a new computer which is classified as an asset within the business.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] According to the accrual basis of accounting, even though the computer has been purchased on credit, the computer is already the property of Quick Services and must be recognised as such.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] As the transaction for the new computer is made *on credit*, the payable "ABC Computers" has not yet been paid.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] As a result, a liability is created within the entity's records.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The journal entry "ABC Computers" is indented to indicate that this is the credit transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] It is accepted accounting practice to indent credit transactions recorded within a journal.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] 500 = 0 + 500 (the accounting equation is therefore balanced).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A business receives cash for a sale: You increase cash (asset) by recording a debit transaction, and increase sales (income) by recording a credit transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A business buys equipment with cash: You increase equipment (asset) by recording a debit transaction, and decrease cash (asset) by recording a credit transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A business borrows with a cash loan: You increase cash (asset) by recording a debit transaction, and increase loan (liability) by recording a credit transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A business pays salaries with cash: You increase salary (expenses) by recording a debit transaction, and decrease cash (asset) by recording a credit transaction.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The totals show the net effect on the accounting equation and the double-entry principle, where the transactions are balanced.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The process of using debits and credits creates a ledger format that resembles the letter "T".
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The term "T-account" is accounting jargon for a "ledger account" and is often used when discussing bookkeeping.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The reason that a ledger account is often referred to as a T-account is due to the way the account is physically drawn on paper (representing a "T").
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] The left column is for debit (Dr) entries, while the right column is for credit (Cr) entries.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] All accounts also can be debited or credited depending on what transaction has taken place.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For example, when a vehicle is purchased using cash, the asset account "Vehicles" is *debited* and simultaneously the asset account "Bank or Cash" is *credited* due to the payment for the vehicle using cash.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Some balance sheet items have corresponding "contra" accounts, with negative balances, that offset them.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Examples are accumulated depreciation, accumulated amortization, and allowance for bad debts (also known as allowance for doubtful accounts) against accounts receivable.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] United States GAAP utilizes the term *contra* for specific accounts only and does not recognize the second half of a transaction as a contra, thus the term is restricted to accounts that are related.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] For example, sales returns and allowance and sales discounts are contra revenues with respect to sales, as the balance of each contra (a debit) is the opposite of sales (a credit).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] To understand the actual value of sales, one must net the contras against sales, which gives rise to the term net sales (meaning net of the contras).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] A more specific definition in common use is an account with a balance that is the opposite of the normal balance (Dr/Cr) for that section of the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] An example is an office coffee fund: Expense "Coffee" (Dr) may be immediately followed by "Coffee – employee contributions" (Cr).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Such an account is used for clarity rather than being a necessary part of GAAP (generally accepted accounting principles).
[src:double-entry-accounting/debits-and-credits] Each of the following accounts is either an Asset (A), Contra Account (CA), Liability (L), Shareholders' Equity (SE), Revenue (Rev), Expense (Exp) or Dividend (Div) account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Every transaction recorded will keep this equation in balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] For example, if a company buys a new piece of equipment (increasing an asset), it can spend cash (reducing an asset) or take on a loan (increasing a liability).
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Based upon where an account sits within the accounting equation determines its normal balance - in this example, a debit to assets *increases* assets, whereas a credit to liabilities *increases* liabilities.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The use of double-entry bookkeeping is a standard process for tracking business transactions that improves the ability of the users of financial information to read, process, and understand the financial picture of a company's operations.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] As the complexity and volume of transactions increases, companies use ledgers and accounting information systems to automate the tracking of individual transactions and to create financial statements.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The earliest extant accounting records that follow the modern double-entry system in Europe come from Amatino Manucci, a Florentine merchant at the end of the 13th century.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Manucci was employed by the Farolfi firm and the firm's ledger of 1299–1300 evidences full double-entry bookkeeping.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Giovannino Farolfi & Company, a firm of Florentine merchants headquartered in Nîmes, acted as moneylenders to the Archbishop of Arles, their most important customer.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Some sources suggest that Giovanni di Bicci de' Medici introduced this method for the Medici bank in the 14th century, though evidence for this is lacking.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The double-entry system began to propagate between Italian merchant cities during the 14th century.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Before this, there may have been systems of accounting records on multiple books which did not yet have the formal and methodical rigor necessary to control the business economy.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] In the course of the 16th century, Venice produced the theoretical accounting science by the writings of Luca Pacioli, Domenico Manzoni, Bartolomeo Fontana, the accountant Alvise Casanova and the erudite Giovanni Antonio Tagliente.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Benedetto Cotrugli (Benedikt Kotruljević), a Ragusan merchant and ambassador to Naples, described double-entry bookkeeping in his treatise *Della mercatura e del mercante perfetto*.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Although it was originally written in 1458, no manuscript older than 1475 is known to remain, and the treatise was not printed until 1573.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The printer shortened and altered Cotrugli's treatment of double-entry bookkeeping, obscuring the history of the subject.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Luca Pacioli, a Franciscan friar and collaborator of Leonardo da Vinci, first codified the system in his mathematics textbook *Summa de arithmetica, geometria, proportioni et proportionalità* published in Venice in 1494.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Pacioli is often called the "father of accounting" because he was the first to publish a detailed description of the double-entry system, thus enabling others to study and use it.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] In early modern Europe, double-entry bookkeeping had theological and cosmological connotations, recalling "both the scales of justice and the symmetry of God's world".
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The double-entry system can be applied using two main methods: the traditional approach (British approach) and the accounting equation approach (American approach).
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Regardless of the method, every transaction maintains two aspects, debit and credit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Irrespective of the approach used, the effect on the books of accounts remains the same, with two aspects (debit and credit) in each of the transactions.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Under the traditional (British) approach, accounts are divided into three categories: real accounts, personal accounts, and nominal accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Real accounts are accounts relating to assets both tangible and intangible in nature.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Personal accounts are accounts relating to persons or organisations with whom the business has transactions and will mainly consist of accounts of debtors and creditors.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Nominal accounts are accounts relating to revenue, expenses, gains, and losses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Personal accounts: Debit the receiver, credit the giver.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Nominal accounts: Debit expenses and losses, credit incomes and gains.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The great importance of the primary journals lies in the fact that they should make it possible to trace every single business transaction back to the original voucher without great effort at any given time during the retention periods, even for past events.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Thus, bank statements can be used as primary journals.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] To simplify or enable the tracking of business transactions in the general ledger, it is necessary to note the account assignment on the original document or to ensure corresponding digital traceability.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The accounting equation is a statement of equality between the debits and the credits.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The rules of debit and credit depend on the nature of an account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] For the purpose of the accounting equation approach, all the accounts are classified into the following five types: assets, capital, liabilities, revenues/incomes, or expenses/losses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] If there is an increase or decrease in a set of accounts, there will be equal decrease or increase in another set of accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] In double-entry bookkeeping, every financial transaction is entered into at least two nominal ledger accounts to ensure that total debits equal total credits, maintaining balance in the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] This is a partial check that each and every transaction has been correctly recorded.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Each transaction is recorded as a "debit entry" (Dr) in one account, and a "credit entry" (Cr) in a second account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Per convention, debits are posted on the left-hand side of a ledger account, while credits are posted on the right-hand side.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] If the total of the entries on the debit side of one account is greater than the total on the credit side of the same nominal account, that account is said to have a debit balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Double entry is applied within nominal ledgers, while daybooks (journals) typically serve as preliminary records and are not part of the nominal ledger itself.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The information from the daybooks will be used in the nominal ledger and it is the nominal ledgers that will ensure the integrity of the resulting financial information created from the daybooks (provided that the information recorded in the daybooks is correct).
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The reason for this is to limit the number of entries in the nominal ledger: entries in the daybooks can be totalled before they are entered in the nominal ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] If there are only a relatively small number of transactions it may be simpler instead to treat the daybooks as an integral part of the nominal ledger and thus of the double-entry system.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] However, as can be seen from the examples of daybooks shown below, it is still necessary to check, within each daybook, that the postings from the daybook balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Nominal ledger accounts form the basis for preparing a trial balance, which lists debit and credit balances in two columns to confirm that total debits equal total credits.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The trial balance lists all the nominal ledger account balances.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The list is split into two columns, with debit balances placed in the left hand column and credit balances placed in the right hand column.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Another column will contain the name of the nominal ledger account describing what each value is for.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The total of the debit column must equal the total of the credit column.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] A debit entry in an account represents a transfer of value *to* that account, and a credit entry represents a transfer *from* the account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Since both sides of a double-entry bookkeeping entry must remain in balance, accounts then have a normal balance, which is based upon whether a debit or a credit increases the account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Due to the format of a ledger, historically debits are recorded on the left side of the ledger, and credits are recorded on the right side of the ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] This may be represented graphically with the use of a T account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Note the normal balance of the account, and whether the transaction is recorded on the left or right side of the ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Transfers the inventory to a customer in exchange for $15,000 of cash.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Pays $10,000 of cash to the vendor for inventory purchased with credit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Note in the example above that both sides of the transaction are equal in each case.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] Also note the normal balance of the account, and which transactions are written on the left or right sides of the ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The net impact of the above transactions are increase in cash of $5,000 and an increase in equity of $5,000 - this is reasonable because the company bought inventory for $10,000 and sold it for $15,000, leaving $5,000 as the profit in the business.
[src:double-entry-accounting/double-entry-bookkeeping] The net impact of all transactions is that the owner's equity in the business has increased by $5,000, because it purchased inventory for $10,000 and in turn sold it to an end customer for $15,000.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] In bookkeeping, a **general ledger** is a bookkeeping ledger in which accounting data are posted from journals and aggregated from subledgers, such as accounts payable, accounts receivable, cash management, fixed assets, purchasing and projects.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] A general ledger may be maintained on paper, on a computer, or in the cloud.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] A ledger account is created for each account in the chart of accounts for an organization and is classified into account categories, such as income, expense, assets, liabilities, and equity; the collection of all these accounts is known as the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The general ledger holds financial and non-financial data for an organization.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] Each account in the general ledger consists of one or more pages.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] It includes details such as the date of sale, invoice number, customer details, and the amount due.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] This ledger helps businesses track outstanding receivables and manage cash flow efficiently.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] An organization's statement of financial position and the income statement are both derived from income and expense account categories in the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The general ledger contains a page for all accounts in the chart of accounts arranged by account categories.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The general ledger is usually divided into at least seven main categories: assets, liabilities, owner's equity, revenue, expenses, gains and losses.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] It is the system of record for an organization’s financial transactions.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The main categories of the general ledger may be further subdivided into subledgers to include additional details of such accounts as cash, accounts receivable, accounts payable, etc.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The extraction of account balances is called a trial balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The purpose of the trial balance is, at a preliminary stage of the financial statement preparation process, to ensure the equality of the total debits and credits.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] Posting is the process of recording amounts as credits (right side), and amounts as debits (left side), in the pages of the general ledger.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] Additional columns to the right hold a running activity total (similar to a chequebook).
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The general ledger should include the date, description and balance or total amount for each account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] Assets = Liabilities + (Shareholder's or Owner's equity).
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] The accounting equation is the mathematical structure of the balance sheet.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] Although a general ledger appears to be fairly simple, in large or complex organizations or organizations with various subsidiaries, the general ledger can grow to be quite large and take several hours or days to audit or balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] In a manual or non-computerized system, the general ledger may be a large book.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] Organizations may instead employ one or more spreadsheets for their ledgers, including the general ledger, or may utilize specialized software to automate ledger entry and handling.
[src:double-entry-accounting/general-ledger] When a business uses enterprise resource planning (ERP) software, a financial-features module produces subledgers and the general ledger, with entries drawn from a database that is shared with other processes managed through the ERP.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] A **trial balance** is an internal financial statement that lists the **adjusted closing balances** of all the general ledger accounts (both revenue and capital) contained in the ledger of a business as at a specific date.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] This list will contain the name of each nominal ledger account in the order of liquidity and the value of that nominal ledger balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] Each nominal ledger account will hold either a debit balance or a credit balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The debit balance values will be listed in the debit column of the trial balance and the credit value balance will be listed in the credit column.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The trading profit and loss statement and balance sheet and other financial reports can then be produced using the ledger accounts listed on the same balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The first published description of the function is found in Luca Pacioli's 1494 work *Summa de arithmetica*, in the section titled *Particularis de Computis et Scripturis*.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] Although he did not use the term, he essentially prescribed a technique similar to a post-closing trial balance.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The primary purpose of preparing a trial balance is to ensure the accuracy of an entity's double-entry bookkeeping system.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] Accounting equation rule states that there must be equal debit and credit for every financial transaction, therefore, the value of all the debit and credit balances on trial balance must be equal.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] If the total of the debit column does not equal the total value of the credit column, then this would show that there is an error in the nominal ledger accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] This error must be found before a profit and loss statement and balance sheet can be produced.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] Hence, trial balance is important in case of adjustments.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] Whenever any adjustment is performed, trial balance should be performed and it should be confirmed whether all the debit amount is equal to credit amount.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The trial balance is usually prepared by a bookkeeper or accountant who has used daybooks to record financial transactions and then post them to the nominal ledgers and personal ledger accounts.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The trial balance is a part of the double-entry bookkeeping system and uses the classic 'T' account format for presenting values.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] Normal Balances refer to whether the balance for an account in a properly-formed trial balance is usually a debt or a credit.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] A normal balance also reflects the accounting equation.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] If a trial balance for an account is reversed, such an account is called a "contra-account" (e.g. accumulated depreciation as an asset or owners drawings as equity).
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The sum total of each column should be equal, or "balance." The act of "closing the books" refers to zeroing out all the revenue and expense amounts at the end of an accounting period (typically a fiscal year) and adding the difference to the retained earnings account.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] This is called a "closing entry." If the company earned a profit, the retained earnings account will be increased.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] If the company experienced a loss, the retained earnings account will be reduced.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The resulting opening balance for the new accounting period will still have columns of equal sum totals.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] A trial balance only checks the sum of debits against the sum of credits.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] That is why it does not guarantee that there are no errors.
[src:double-entry-accounting/trial-balance] The following are the main classes of errors that are not detected by the trial balance.
